{"rawJson":null,"m_plot":"During a diplomatic visit to Toronto, the U.S. President Adam Scott (Hal Holbrook) is abducted by a South American terrorist, Roberto Assanti (Miguel Fernandes), and his female accomplice, and is held captive in an armored truck booby-trapped with high explosives. The elaborate bomb keeps the Secret Service at bay until Assanti is killed. However, the explosives are timed to detonate at midnight, so Secret Service agent Jerry O'Connor (Shatner) has to find a way into the truck to rescue the President before it detonates. Also involved are U.S Vice-President Ethan Richards (Johnson) and his wife Beth (Gardner).","m_cast":null,"m_reception":null,"m_production":null,"m_sequel":null,"m_based_on":null,"m_directed_by":"George Mendeluk","m_produced_by":"George Mendeluk John Ryan","m_screenplay_by":null,"m_story_by":null,"m_starring":"William Shatner Hal Holbrook Van Johnson Ava Gardner","m_music_by":"Nash the Slash Paul Zaza","m_cinematography":"Mike Molloy","m_edited_by":"Michael MacLaverty","m_production_company":null,"m_distributed_by":"Crown International Pictures","m_release_dates":"15 August 1980 19 September 1980","m_running_time":"114 min","m_country":"Canada / United States","m_language":"English | The Kidnapping of the President is a 1980 political thriller film made by Presidential Films and Sefel Films and distributed by Crown International Pictures. It was produced and directed by George Mendeluk and co-produced by John Ryan from a screenplay by Richard Murphy and Charles Templeton, based on Templeton's novel. The original music was by Nash the Slash and Paul Zaza and the cinematography by Mike Molloy. | The film stars William Shatner, Hal Holbrook, Van Johnson and Ava Gardner.","m_budget":null,"m_box_office":null,"m_marketing":null,"m_reference":null,"m_external_link":"The Kidnapping of the President at the Internet Movie Database | ","m_poster":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0a/Kidnapping_of_the_president.jpeg/22